Certainly! Here is an example of a basic Backpropagation (BP) algorithm code in Matlab that implements a simple neural network:

```
% Generate a toy dataset for illustration
X = [0 0; 0 1; 1 0; 1 1];
Y = [0; 1; 1; 0];

% Set the number of hidden units and learning rate
hidden_units = 2;
learning_rate = 0.1;

% Initialize weights randomly
W1 = randn(size(X,2), hidden_units);
W2 = randn(hidden_units,1);

% Set the number of epochs to train for
epochs = 10000;

% Train the network using backpropagation
for i = 1:epochs
    % Forward pass
    H = 1./(1 + exp(-X*W1));
    Y_hat = 1./(1 + exp(-H*W2));

    % Compute the error and delta at the output layer
    error = Y - Y_hat;
    delta2 = error.*(Y_hat.*(1-Y_hat));

    % Compute the delta at the hidden layer
    delta1 = delta2*W2'.*(H.*(1-H));

    % Update the weights
    W1 = W1 + learning_rate*X'*delta1;
    W2 = W2 + learning_rate*H'*delta2;    
end
```

This code trains a neural network to perform the XOR function on a toy dataset with two input variables `X(:,1)` and `X(:,2)` and one output `Y`. It uses a single hidden layer with two hidden units and the sigmoid activation function. 

Note: This is a very simple example of a BP algorithm. In practice, BP is often implemented with additional optimizations, such as momentum, regularization, mini-batch processing, etc.
